        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging requirements:
We propose to achieve an angular resolution of 0.35''. This is 
sufficient to separate the two outflow lobes predicted by our 
simulation and therefore unambiguously detect an outflow 
signature. First-core outflows could have an extent of up to 
about 1000 AU, i.e. about 7'' at 150 pc. Following the 
recommendation of the Observing Tool, we do not need to 
complement the main-array observations with the ACA in order to 
probe emission up to this angular scale.

Correlator setup:
We propose to use two basebands to map the line emission in 
CO 3--2 and, as a bonus, 13CO 3--2, and two basebands to map the 
continuum emission. For the line observations, we request an 
effective spectral resolution of 122 kHz (0.1 km/s) and a 
bandwidth of 234 MHz. 

Requested sensitivity:
We propose to achieve an rms sensitivity of 0.3 K (3.59 mJy) at 
an effective spectral resolution of 0.3 km/s for the line 
observations. This will yield a signal-to-noise ratio of 7, 
sufficient to measure the peak position and strength of the 
outflow lobes with good accuracy (HPBW/2/7=0.025'' and 14%, 
respectively). The accuracy should even be better since we 
expect to detect each outflow lobe over a few channels.
The rms sensitivity achieved in continuum will be 
33 microJy/0.35''-beam. For comparison, the first-core candidate 
L1451-mm has a peak flux density of 27 mJy/1.2''x0.9''-beam at 
230 GHz and 250 pc (Pineda et al. 2011), i.e. 5 mJy in a 
0.35''-beam at 150 pc, if the emitting region is extended and 
its flux density scales with the radius. At 345 GHz, its flux 
density would be somewhat higher. Therefore, the continuum 
sensitivity that will be obtained here for Cha-MMS1 will be 
largely sufficient to pinpoint the precise position of the first 
core and verify that the outflow is centered on it.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
